        <body>

            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><date>Friday&#44; 18 Sivan &#40;May&#41;&#44; 1850</date>&#44;
                    <placeName>New York</placeName></p>
            <p>Peace to the honor of my friend&#8230;the author<lb/>&#8230;seeker of the welfare of
                all <placeName>America</placeName>&#44; the<lb/> near and the far.
                    <addressee>Eliezer Lesser</addressee> etc.</p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#44;</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I come to beg of your Honor to try to<lb/> find for me a
                dwelling&#82211;place where I can<lb/> serve the Holy Cause&#44; to preside over
                the<lb/> sacrifice &#40;&#91;&#41;Prayer&#40;&#92;&#41; and to be a hazan and rabbi.
                For<lb/> it is my intention to move my residence from<lb/> the City of
                    <placeName>Utica</placeName> to whatever place I may<lb/> find and which God may
                send my way.<lb/> I cannot any longer and I do not want<lb/> to stay in
                    <placeName>Utica</placeName> because of the wickedness<lb/> of its inhabitants.
                To write down all their<lb/> wicked deeds&#44; how evil and sinful they<lb/> are to
                God and man&#44; would make a<lb/> big book&#44; <del>and</del> for <sic>their</sic>
                is no measuring nor<lb/> describing it.<lb/>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am sure that are looking to<lb/> appoint for themselves a
                Shohet<lb/> and Hazan&#44; or even a rabbi and<lb/> perhaps a preacher too&#44; if
                they seek the<lb/> truth&#44; will&#44; I trust to God&#44; derive much</p>

            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>joy from a man like me. As to this there<lb/> is the testimony of all the sages of
                    <placeName>Germany</placeName><lb/> and <placeName>Poland</placeName>. Their
                letters are in my bag&#59;<lb/> letters of permission to be shohet&#44; and<lb/> to
                act as rabbi&#44; all announce and testify<lb/> about me that I am fit for that
                    <del>job</del><lb/> honor. All the congregation that wants<lb/> to choose me can
                investigate about<lb/> me by inquiring of the rabbi and<lb/> great preacher
                    <persName>Doctor Raphall</persName>&#44; and<lb/> of my friend the pious Mohel
                    <persName>Shneor<lb/> NÃ¼ssbaum</persName>&#44; and of other prominent<lb/> men
                here. But my ways are not known<lb/> to the world in general&#59; nor do wise
                men<lb/> boast&#59; as the wise man said &#8220;Let a<lb/> stranger praise thee not
                thine own mouth&#8221;<lb/> Nevertheless&#44; in the case of a man <hi
                    rend="underline">whose<lb/> future seems dark</hi>. <del>be right</del>
                &#40;or&#44; perhaps&#44;<lb/> the writer meant&#44; &#8220;who is very
                modest&#8221;&#41;<lb/> his way will remain dark if he does not<lb/> anyone of his
                nature and doings. He<lb/> should not be despised if he makes him<lb/> self
                public&#44; to tell mankind of his</p>

            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>prowess&#44; and let his friends praise<lb/> him in the gate.<lb/></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">When I arrived here last night<lb/> and went to the home of
                    <persName>Doctor Raphall</persName><lb/> and asked him whether he knew a
                resting<lb/> place for me. He told me that <placeName>Chicago</placeName><lb/> seeks
                a Shohet and Hazan. That is<lb/> why I lay my urgent plea before you<lb/>
                <del>to forego your pret pride</del> begging your pardon a thousand times and urging
                you write<lb/> to them to choose me rather than the<lb/> others. You know those
                others and<lb/> their kind. If you&#44; honored Sir&#44; are<lb/> willing to do
                this&#44; please write at<lb/> once&#44; by the first post. In return<lb/> you will
                have peace in this world and<lb/> the next because you had mercy on<lb/> a humble
                soul like me and caused<lb/> sighing spirits to rejoice&#59; i.e. my<lb/> wife and
                son whose eyes look<lb/> to me. How can I help them&#63; Where<lb/> is the
                store&#8211;house or the wine&#8211;press&#63;<lb/> I therefore hope in your good
                nature</p>

            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>place as shohet and Hazan&#44; I shall<lb/> pay to your Honor a portion of my<lb/>
                salary up to twenty dollars</p>
            <p>The last in <del>t<add>&#63;</add></del> small letters<lb/> at bottom</p>
            <p>On very top his address</p>
            <p><persName>P. Rosenthal</persName><lb/>
                <placeName>Utica N. Y.</placeName><lb/> No. 1 Hatel<add>&#63;</add> Av.</p>


        </body>
